What Is Geofencing and How Does It Work?
Geofencing is a location-based marketing technology that triggers automated actions when mobile devices enter or exit predefined geographic boundaries. These boundaries, called geofences, can range from a small area as tight as a single building entrance to larger zones encompassing entire business parks or conference venues. When a device crosses the geofence boundary, the geofencing platform detects this movement and can immediately execute predetermined marketing actions.

The technical foundation of geofencing involves several key components working in coordination. GPS (Global Positioning System) provides location accuracy for geofencing, though newer technologies increasingly employ alternative positioning methods including cellular triangulation, WiFi signals, and Bluetooth beacons to supplement GPS, especially in areas where GPS signals prove unreliable such as building interiors or urban canyons surrounded by tall buildings.

How precisely can geofencing target locations? Modern geofencing technology enables accuracy ranges from 5 to 100 feet, depending on the technology stack employed. For B2B applications, 50-100 foot accuracy proves sufficient to identify prospects entering specific office buildings or conference areas, while tighter accuracy levels work well for retail or experiential applications.

The marketing action triggered when a device enters a geofence can vary considerably. Most commonly, marketers push notifications to users' mobile devices, deliver targeted ads within apps or mobile browsers, trigger email sequences, add contacts to CRM records with location tags, or create audience segments for subsequent retargeting campaigns. Advanced implementations trigger multiple coordinated actions simultaneously—perhaps both a mobile push notification and an immediate email while simultaneously tagging the contact in CRM for sales team follow-up.

What makes geofencing particularly powerful for B2B applications? The ability to connect physical presence with digital action at scale. An enterprise software company can geofence a competitor's headquarters, automatically identifying prospects visiting that location and immediately delivering comparison content and competitive positioning messaging. A manufacturing software vendor can geofence industry conferences, identifying attending prospects and triggering personalized follow-up sequences aligned with their specific roles and company characteristics.

